items.title: setlist can't be reversed
items.body:
Using collections_extended v1.0.3:

A `setlist` can't be reversed with `reverse` method:

```python
from collections_extended import setlist
l = setlist("abc")
l.reverse()
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "<input>", line 1, in <module>
  File ".../_collections_abc.py", line 985, in reverse
    self[i], self[n-i-1] = self[n-i-1], self[i]
  File ".../collections_extended/setlists.py", line 330, in __setitem__
    raise ValueError
ValueError
```

This is because the original implementation (`_collections_abc.MutableSequence.reverse`) uses the "swap" technique.

items.title: Add counts method to bags
items.body:
Return a generator? View?
Deprecate `nlargest`. Add a `most_frequent` parameter to bag.counts to replace it.
Or maybe a `sort`='asc' or 'desc' and a `limit` parameter?
Or maybe just have people use `heapq` themselves if they want.

`_basebag._dict.items()` is used all over the place in the code and replacing it with a `counts` method would make the code more implementation agnostic. This would make things like allowing unhashable elements easier.

items.title: Document bag operators
items.body:
Bags support operators but this isn't documented:

- &: interesection
- |: union
- +: sum
- -: difference
- *: Cartesian product
- ^: symmetric difference

items.title: Adding indexed dictionary?
items.body:
Hi, sorry for asking this in an issue, but I couldn't find any better place.

I made a `IndexedDict` data structure (basically a dict and a list tied together), mostly compatible with `OrderedDict`. In addition to OrderedDict it allows access either by key or by index and converting between keys and indices. Most of operations run in O(1), deleting from the middle and `move_to_end` in O(n).

Currently I consider it complete and I also have 99% coverage py.test tests. However there is no documentation other than docstrings and I haven't tested on any other python version than 3.6.5.

Would you be interested in adding a data structure like this to collections-extended? I'm asking before going ahead with a pull request because the class is perfectly usable for me now and I don't want to put much more effort in it if it goes unused.

Preview:
https://github.com/bluecube/parametric/blob/master/parametric/util/indexed_dict.py
https://github.com/bluecube/parametric/blob/master/tests/test_indexed_dict.py

items.title: RangeMap: No way to get end of highest range?
items.body:
I couldn't find any way to get the end of the highest range from a RangeMap. For example:

```
rm = RangeMap()
rm[5:10] = 'test'
print(max(rm))  # output: 5
```

I would expect `10`, or expect some other way of getting this.

I've created #85 as a possibility to address this.

items.title: Constructing `bag` or `setlist` is slow compared to `set`
items.body:
About a hundred times slower:

```
>>> timeit.timeit("set('abracadabra'*10000)", number=100)
0.11974816499423468

>>> timeit.timeit("bag('abracadabra'*10000)", setup='from collections_extended import bag', number=100)
12.000456281995866

>>> timeit.timeit("setlist('abracadabra'*10000)", setup='from collections_extended import setlist', number=100)
11.53152776099887
```

Are there any plans to improve the performance or is it not a concern? I suppose a C extension would be necessary.

items.title: frozen and mutable variants of bag/setlist should have different str representations
items.body:
`__str__` is the same for bag/frozenbag and setlist/frozensetlist. This doesn't match the behavior of built in set.

Also see #69.

items.title: setlist optionally raise error in __init__ for duplicate values
items.body:
Currently `setlist.__init__` behaves like `update` as opposed to `extend`. The decision had to be made one way or the other and in addition to having code assuming it behaved this way, the behavior matched `Set.__init__`. However, it would be nice to be able to raise Errors upon creation. This is particularly useful for a `frozensetlist` where we can't call `extend` afterwards.

There are two options - either pass a flag as a keyword argument to `__init__` or create a new classmethod to create setlists this way.

Related to #23

items.title: New str(setlist)?
items.body: `setlist.__str__` returns the same string as a normal list, is there a better alternative? It would be nice to have a unique representation. Maybe `str(setlist(range(3))) == '{[1, 2, 3}]'`

items.title: setlist.extend doesn't properly handle duplicate values in the new values
items.body:
Extending a setlist with duplicate values leaves all of the values up to the second copy of any value in the setlist:

```
>>> sl = setlist()
>>> sl.extend('baa')
    ValueError...
>>> sl
    setlist(('b', 'a',))
```

The operation should be atomic, all values should be added or none.

items.title: setlist operater implementation
items.body:
Implementation is currently incomplete and inconsistent.
`__iadd__` is implemented, but `__add__` isn't
`__iadd__` does Sequence extend where `__sub__` does Set difference

Choose either Set or Sequence implementation.
Operations (**add**, **iadd**, etc.) should all either behave like Set or Sequence.

items.title: Add setlist.update
items.body:
Like extend, but silently ignore duplicate values.

We have add/append, remove/discard, remove_all/discard_all but missing the set equivalent for extend.

```
>>> r[1:] = 3
```

items.title: RangeMap del should raise a KeyError if the range isn't mapped
items.body:
```
rm = RangeMap({1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c', 4: 'd', 5: 'e'})
del rm[2:3]
del rm[2:3]
```

Second should raise an error

```
rm = RangeMap({1: 'a', 2: 'b', 3: 'c', 4: 'd', 5: 'e'})
del rm[0:2]
```

Should raise an error.

items.title: bag.__isub__ will raise a ValueError and remove some elements if one isn't present
items.body: Should we first check that we can remove all of the elements first, raise a ValueError if we can't, and if we can then remove all of the elements. Then we won't be left in a state where only some elements get removed.

items.title: setlist - Rename remove_all to discard_all?
items.body: `remove_all` matches the behavior of `discard` not `remove` in that it doesn't raise ValueErrors and just ignores elements to be removed that aren't present.

items.title: setlist.add should not raise ValueError if the value is already present

Collection comparison
items.body:
What types of Collections should be comparable to each other?
If a set and a bag contain the same elements with the same multiplicity
should they be equal?  For a list and a setlist?

I think sets and bags should be comparable, a bag can be a subset of a set
and vice versa.  The relationship is well defined and already in Python for
set comparisons.
